                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.841 Surtax/6: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-07-12T14:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 12, 1927—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>282. Your 718, July 11, 5 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Department does not understand necessity of reserving position of American
                        Government at Diplomatic Body meeting as Department’s 280 of July 9, 2 p.m.,
                        informed you that the Department saw no objection to protesting against
                        tonnage dues collected in violation of treaty.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Representative of Robert Dollar Company called at the Department today
                        with regard to question of tonnage dues and was informed in accordance with
                        statement contained in telegram of July 7, 9 p.m., from American Consul at
                        Shanghai quoted in your 705 of July 8, 3 p.m. that the American Consul at
                        Shanghai had already protested against the tonnage tax.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
